// bisect: fusion/JIT bug (interp != jit)
// interp: Trace([0:42 1:42 2:42 3:42 4:42 5:42]) — re-emits EVERY cycle
// jit:    Trace([0:42]) — CORRECT (fires when its inputs fired: once)
// Found by soak-jul05, fuzz campaign seed 70501 (corpus-fuzz/
// divergence_000008 — the original rode a queuefn feedback loop whose
// cycles made an array::group close at count 3 in the interp only).
// root_cause: NODE-WALK over-fire. FoldQ::update's empty-array arm
// (`if self.nodes.is_empty() && self.arr_present { self.init.clone() }`,
// graphix-package-core) returns Some(init) UNCONDITIONALLY on every
// update call once the empty array has arrived — one spurious emit
// per cycle any event flows anywhere in the graph. The kernel's
// firing rule for the same shape is `src-fired ∧ empty` (+ init fire
// via the chain), which is the fired-bit-principled behavior — the
// same family as the #8 tail-loop over-fire and the same verdict:
// fix the node-walk. The empty arm must emit only when the array arg
// or the init arg actually fired this cycle.
// minimized:
{seq(i64:0, i64:5)$; array::fold(array::init(i64:0, |i: i64| i), i64:42, |a, x| a + x)}
